The '''Lau'agae Ridge Quarry''' is a prehistoric stone quarry on the eastern side of the island of [[Tutuila]] in the United States territory of [[American Samoa]].  It is located on a ridge above another archaeological site, the prehistoric village of [[Tulauta Village Site|Tulauta]].  The site includes a carpet of stone flakes, evidence of rough stonework (creating forms probably finished in Tulauta), signs of habitation, and two ''tia'ave'', oval stone platforms found in abundance on the island.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Prehistoric Settlement System in Eastern Tutuila, America Samoa|last=Clark|first=Jeffrey|last2=Herdrich|first2=David|journal=The Journal of the Polynesian Society|issue=Volume 102, No. 2|date=June 1993|pages=147–185}}</ref>

The quarry site was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2000.<ref name="nris"/>

