In the [[ancient history|ancient world]], '''Thynia''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|θ|ɪ|n|i|ə}}, {{lang-el|Θυνία}}) was a region of Europe along the northern coast of the [[Propontis]], opposite [[Bithynia]] on the [[Asia Minor|Asian]] side.<ref>W.H.Race, ''Apollonius Rhodius: Argonautica'', Loeb Classical Library (2008), introductory maps</ref> It was occupied by the [[Thyni]], a [[Thracians|Thracian]] people who came from [[Thrace]].  Note that in the Middle Ages, [[Mesothynia]] ("middle Thynia") was the peninsula of modern [[Kocaeli Peninsula|Kocaeli]].

According to Greek mythology, its name came from Thyneas (Θυνέας) son of Phineas (Φινέας).

In the [[Argonautica]] (Book 2), [[Jason]] and the Argonauts are turned aside from the Clashing Rocks at Bithynia, and go to the opposite coast to consult King Phineus.

