'''Xenagoras''' ({{lang-grc|Ξεναγόρας}}) was a [[Greek historiography|Greek historian]] quoted by [[Dionysius of Halicarnassus]],<ref>[[Dionysius of Halicarnassus]], i. 72</ref> from whom we learn that Xenagoras wrote that [[Odysseus]] and Circe had three sons, [[Rhomos]], [[Anteias]], and [[Ardeas]], who founded the three cities which were called by their names. He wrote a work titled ''Chronicle'' (Χρόνοι),<ref>[[Scholiast]] on [[Apollonius of Rhodes]] iv. 262, 264</ref><ref>[[Harpocration]] ''s.v.'' Κραυαλλίδαι</ref> and another on islands (Περὶ νήσων).<ref>Etymol. ''s.v.'' Σφήκεια</ref><ref>[[John Tzetzes]], ''On [[Lycophron]]'' 447</ref><ref>[[Harpocration]] ''s.v.'' Χύτροι</ref><ref>[[Stephanus of Byzantium]] ''s.v.'' Χύτροι</ref><ref>[[Gerardus Vossius]], ''de Historicis Graecis p. 508, ed. Westermann</ref><ref>[[Henry Fynes Clinton]], ''Fasti Hellenici'' vol. iii. p. 566</ref> The 5th century writer [[Macrobius]] also refers to the third book of the history of Xenagoras.<ref>[[Macrobius]], v. 19</ref>

This Xenagoras was possibly the same Xenagoras as father of the historian [[Nymphis]].

